      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Greg" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Greg" href="/user/show/39346323-greg">Greg</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/39346323-greg?shelf=who-did-it">who-did-it</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/39346323-greg?shelf=20th-century">20th-century</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/39346323-greg?shelf=reviewed">reviewed</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2966232584" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer18381617322448045391">&quot;Why on earth did &apos;x&apos; kill &apos;x&apos;? More than anything else, Tommy [Lynley], that seems so senseless to me,&quot; says a character on page 368 of 374. The author realizes the inclusion of a stupendously brutal 2nd (or 3rd, depending on how you see the time-line) murder of a 16 y/0 kid was a huge mistake: sadistic only for shock value. With a minute of editing, George could have removed that murder and the story would have worked...maybe. I lost track of who was going to bed with who at the 200-page mark,</span>
  <span id="freeText18381617322448045391" style="display:none">"Why on earth did 'x' kill 'x'? More than anything else, Tommy [Lynley], that seems so senseless to me," says a character on page 368 of 374. The author realizes the inclusion of a stupendously brutal 2nd (or 3rd, depending on how you see the time-line) murder of a 16 y/0 kid was a huge mistake: sadistic only for shock value. With a minute of editing, George could have removed that murder and the story would have worked...maybe. I lost track of who was going to bed with who at the 200-page mark, and the 'if things get all jumbled, have someone be a Russian spy" trope distraction at the 300-page mark had me laughing. I'll assume this is the low-point of this series and try one more. Given the awesomely bad debuts of Ruth Rendell, Margery Allingham, and Dorothy Sayers, I gave this one a 2nd star for the sake of relativity.</span>
  <a data-text-id="18381617322448045391" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


