<div id="review_1914743431" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1914743431" />
    <a title="Larry Bassett" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3816725-larry-bassett"><img alt="Larry Bassett" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1390874855p2/3816725.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1914743431?book_show_action=true">Feb 24, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Larry Bassett" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Larry Bassett" href="/user/show/3816725-larry-bassett">Larry Bassett</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/8132843-payment-in-blood">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3816725-larry-bassett?shelf=audio">audio</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3816725-larry-bassett?shelf=mystery">mystery</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1914743431" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9321945228015903666">You will have to read my words in the review of the first book in the series to get my overall enthusiasm for this author. This is a 1989 work of art. It seems right to me to call this book elegant. I like this author very much. This is a pretty old series these days. The setting is mostly an English estate house and the whole book has a bit of an old-time feeling to it. And English nobility plays a bit of a role in the book.<br/><br/>As mysteries go this one ranked pretty well. It is in the old style of </span>
  <span id="freeText9321945228015903666" style="display:none">You will have to read my words in the review of the first book in the series to get my overall enthusiasm for this author. This is a 1989 work of art. It seems right to me to call this book elegant. I like this author very much. This is a pretty old series these days. The setting is mostly an English estate house and the whole book has a bit of an old-time feeling to it. And English nobility plays a bit of a role in the book.<br /><br />As mysteries go this one ranked pretty well. It is in the old style of eight or 10 characters snowed in in an old house when the murder takes place. So we know one of the guests is a murderer. By the end of the book more than several of them have seem to be the prime suspect. I never have been one to want to figure out murder mysteries before the end so I enjoyed being manipulated along throughout. <br /><br />The strong woman is the second in command in this series and she is and enjoyably strong character. She has a positive relationship with her boss and you couldn't say she knuckles under him much. This is an enjoyable book to listen to.</span>
  <a data-text-id="9321945228015903666" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


